00:01:42.560 --> 00:01:48.310
Let's start with the basics: gravity near
Earth's surface. In studying Newton's Laws

00:01:48.310 --> 00:01:55.310
we all learn that F = ma. Near Earth's surface,
that "a," acceleration, is provided by Earth's

00:01:56.450 --> 00:02:02.060
gravity. The value is almost constant, so
we use this small "g" constant to represent

00:02:02.060 --> 00:02:03.520
it.

00:02:03.520 --> 00:02:10.360
We're all familiar with the most basic applications
of gravity - that we stay on the ground, that

00:02:10.360 --> 00:02:16.520
objects fall downward, that we have to work
harder walking up a hill than down.

00:02:16.520 --> 00:02:20.480
There are also many applications of gravity
that are hidden from us in our day-to-day

00:02:20.480 --> 00:02:28.100
experience. For instance, elevators use counterweights
to ease the load on the motor. As gravity

00:02:28.110 --> 00:02:33.420
pulls on the counterweight, the tension it
puts on the cable pulls the elevator upward

00:02:33.420 --> 00:02:39.480
and helps to balance the force of gravity
on the elevator itself.

00:02:39.480 --> 00:02:46.030
Some older mountain railways also use counterbalancing,
with one train car moving upward as the other

00:02:46.030 --> 00:02:48.280
moves down.

00:02:48.280 --> 00:02:53.010
Pile drivers are construction machines that
rely on the pull of gravity to slam large

00:02:53.010 --> 00:03:00.010
weights into the ground, digging holes and
driving foundations for buildings.

00:03:00.709 --> 00:03:06.650
As useful as this simple view of gravity is,
it's fairly limited - it can't explain why

00:03:06.650 --> 00:03:11.459
the planets are spherical instead of, say,
cube-shaped. It also can't explain the orbits

00:03:11.459 --> 00:03:17.050
of the planets, or the action of the tides.
Let's move to a more complex expression for

00:03:17.050 --> 00:03:21.800
gravity that can help us understand these
things.

00:03:21.800 --> 00:03:27.110
Newton's law of universal gravitation is a
powerful model that can explain many different

00:03:27.110 --> 00:03:31.430
phenomena. Let's dive right in.

00:03:31.430 --> 00:03:36.709
Unlike the most basic view of gravity, in
which it pulls straight down, leaving Canadians

00:03:36.709 --> 00:03:42.790
to wonder why penguins don't fall off the
planet, Newton's gravity shows that all objects

00:03:42.790 --> 00:03:49.790
are pulled toward each other's centers. Thus,
we all stay firmly planted on Earth's surface.

00:03:51.050 --> 00:03:56.099
Because the gravitational force pulls equally
in all directions, large bodies in space tend

00:03:56.099 --> 00:04:03.099
to be spherical. The Sun, all planets, and
even larger moons tend towards a spherical

00:04:03.130 --> 00:04:04.950
shape for this reason.

00:04:04.950 --> 00:04:11.069
Newton's law of gravity also means that all
objects are pulled toward each other, such

00:04:11.069 --> 00:04:16.839
as planets toward the sun. By solving the
differential equations that come from this

00:04:16.839 --> 00:04:22.370
law, we can obtain the elliptical orbits that
all planets have as they move around their

00:04:22.370 --> 00:04:23.219
stars.

00:04:23.219 --> 00:04:29.229
We can get all sorts of ellipses, from the
near-circles we see in the inner planets,

00:04:29.229 --> 00:04:36.229
to Pluto's elongated orbit, to comets that
swing far out of the solar system.

00:04:36.479 --> 00:04:42.099
The smaller pulls that planets have toward
each other can be useful too. They're what

00:04:42.099 --> 00:04:48.029
allowed us to discover Neptune, by looking
at the disturbances in the orbit of Uranus.

00:04:48.029 --> 00:04:55.029
Newton's law of gravity also gave us new insight
into events on Earth, like our tides. Objects

00:04:56.449 --> 00:05:01.439
on one side of the Earth are pulled more strongly
toward the moon than objects on the other

00:05:01.439 --> 00:05:06.699
side, in a phenomenon called tidal forces.

00:05:06.699 --> 00:05:13.699
Our own galaxy, the Milky Way, has gravitational
interactions with other smaller galaxies nearby.

00:05:13.999 --> 00:05:20.620
Its disc-like shape and spiral arms may have
come from tearing those galaxies apart.

00:05:20.620 --> 00:05:25.930
We see other galaxies colliding in many other
places in the universe, as gravity pulls them

00:05:25.930 --> 00:05:30.259
together. It actually seems to be fairly common.

00:05:30.259 --> 00:05:36.819
Speaking of galaxies, Newton's law also tells
us how fast galaxies should rotate. We can

00:05:36.819 --> 00:05:41.860
predict a particular A curve for how fast
the stars will be moving according to their

00:05:41.860 --> 00:05:48.009
distance from the center - that's curve A
here. But when we measure the actual velocity

00:05:48.009 --> 00:05:54.419
of those stars, we get B curve B instead.
This was our first indication of the existence

00:05:54.419 --> 00:05:59.990
of dark matter - some sort of substance that
produces gravity but doesn't interact with

00:05:59.990 --> 00:06:06.710
light. We couldn't see it, but we could see
its effects. Dark matter surrounds and is

00:06:06.710 --> 00:06:13.430
part of every galaxy. In fact, there's so
much that it makes up most of the galaxy!

00:06:13.430 --> 00:06:18.129
Physicists are still trying to figure out
what this dark matter might be.

00:06:18.129 --> 00:06:23.669
We can also use Newton's law of gravity to
look beyond the structure of individual galaxies

00:06:23.669 --> 00:06:30.669
- we can look at clusters of galaxies, superclusters,
