00:07:12.110 --> 00:07:19.069
A real triumph of Newton's approach was that
it worked for everything from people on Earth

00:07:19.069 --> 00:07:24.249
out to some of the most distant objects we
can see.

00:07:24.249 --> 00:07:30.270
But it couldn't handle everything, and that's
why we need this next part.

00:07:30.270 --> 00:07:35.759
The most powerful model of gravity is described
by Einstein's field equations, which are the

00:07:35.759 --> 00:07:41.589
core of general relativity. This equation
may not make sense to you now, but later in

00:07:41.589 --> 00:07:47.699
your career you may learn about something
called tensors, which are related to vectors.

00:07:47.699 --> 00:07:53.899
In this equation, tensors describe the gravitational
effects of both matter and energy on all

00:07:53.899 --> 00:08:01.639
things around them. This equation is very
hard to solve, even for experts. Some of the

00:08:01.649 --> 00:08:06.830
cases we know how to solve tell us about black
holes and gravitational lensing, and give

00:08:06.830 --> 00:08:13.169
us insight into the universe when it was very young.

00:08:13.169 --> 00:08:18.520
Black holes were one of the first solutions
to Einstein's field equations. You've probably

00:08:18.520 --> 00:08:24.300
heard of black holes, which are objects so
massive that they warp space and time, and

00:08:24.300 --> 00:08:27.589
even light cannot escape their gravitational pull.

00:08:27.589 --> 00:08:35.078
At the center of our galaxy, and of many large
galaxies, are supermassive black holes. We

00:08:35.078 --> 00:08:42.078
can see their effects as stars near the center
of the galaxy whip around them at high speed.

00:08:42.149 --> 00:08:48.060
While black holes trap light, other massive
objects can have an effect too. Light bends

00:08:48.060 --> 00:08:52.740
in its path as it moves past heavy objects
like stars.

00:08:52.740 --> 00:08:57.880
This can lead to gravitational lensing, in
which light from a distant object is bent

00:08:57.880 --> 00:09:04.240
around both sides of a heavy object. This
lets us see multiple views of an object, or

00:09:04.240 --> 00:09:06.630
even warped images.

00:09:06.630 --> 00:09:13.630
Einstein's field equations also include this
lambda value: the cosmological constant.

00:09:13.779 --> 00:09:20.259
This value can be used to describe a universe
that collapses or holds steady, expands slowly,

00:09:20.259 --> 00:09:25.949
or expands at an accelerating rate. Astronomers
are working to measure this value, and we

00:09:25.949 --> 00:09:32.019
seem to be in the third case - a universe
that expands faster and faster.

00:09:32.019 --> 00:09:36.959
Einstein's theory of gravity remains one of
the best-tested and most accurate theories

00:09:36.959 --> 00:09:43.410
in all of science. It can explain everything
that Newtonian gravity can and more, things

00:09:43.410 --> 00:09:48.589
we wouldn't otherwise be able to predict or
understand, it can even make predictions about how

00:09:48.589 --> 00:09:54.790
the universe will end. You can see why people
would be interested in studying it.

00:09:54.790 --> 00:10:00.860
These three gravitational equations describe
a huge range of phenomena in our natural world,

00:10:00.860 --> 00:10:06.180
from things in our own home to the farthest
objects we can see. I hope that you will be

00:10:06.180 --> 00:10:11.670
motivated to learn more about them. Understanding
